===Etymology===
{{rfscript|Gothic}}
{{etyl|enm}} {{term|crien|crien||lang=enm}} from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|crier|crier||lang=fro}} from {{etyl|ML.}} {{term|cridare|crīdāre|to cry out, proclaim|lang=la}}, of disputed origin. Akin to {{etyl|oc|-}} {{term|cridar|cridar||lang=oc}}, {{etyl|ita|-}} {{term|gridare|gridare||lang=ita}}, {{etyl|osp|-}} {{term|cridar|cridar||lang=osp}} ({{etyl|es|-}} {{term|gritar|gritar||lang=es}}). Attempts have been made to connect the word to {{etyl|la}} ''[[queri]]'' "to complain" (cf Latin ''[[quiritare]]'' "to wail, shriek"), though the phonetic and semantic developments are difficult to explain (the original meaning of ''cry'' was that of "shout, yell, proclaim", not "complain, lament, wail"). Alternate sources (--Littré) trace {{etyl|ML.}} {{term|cridare|crīdāre||lang=la}} to a {{etyl|gem}} source, {{etyl|frk}} *{{term||krītan|to cry, cry out, publish|lang=frk}} or {{etyl|got}} {{term|kriten|criten, kriten|to cry, scream, call out|lang=}}, both from {{proto|Germanic|krītanan|to cry out, shout|lang=en}} from {{proto|Indo-European|greid-|to shout|lang=en}}, making it cognate with {{etyl|dum|-}} {{term|criten|crīten||lang=osx}} ({{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|krijten|krijten||lang=nl}} "to cry"), {{etyl|gml|-}} {{term|kriten|krīten|to cry, call out, shriek|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|gmh|-}} {{term|krizen|krīzen||lang=gmh}} "to cry loudly, wail, groan" ({{etyl|de|-}} {{term|kreissen|kreissen||lang=de}}). Cf also Sanskrit ''cvas'' "to [[pant]]", "[[hiss]]", "[[sigh]]"; {{en}} ''[[quarrel]]'' a brawl, ''[[querulous]]''.

{{enm}} {{term|crien|crien||lang=enm}} displaced native {{enm}} ''[[galen#Middle English|galen]]'' "to cry out" (from {{ang}} ''[[galan#Old English|galan]]''), {{enm}} ''[[greden#Middle English|greden]]'' "to cry out" (from {{ang}} ''[[grædan#Old English|grǣdan]]''), {{enm}} ''[[yermen#Middle English|yermen]]'' "to bellow, mourn, lament" (from {{ang}} ''[[gierman#Old English|ġierman]]''), {{enm}} ''[[hoen#Middle English|hooen, hoen]]'' "to cry out" (from {{non}} ''[[hoa#Old Norse|hōa]]''), {{enm}} ''[[remen#Middle English|remen]]'' "to cry, shout" (from {{ang}} ''[[hrieman#Old English|hrīeman]]'', cf {{ang}} ''[[hream#Old English|hrēam]]'' "noise, outcry, lamentation, alarm"), {{enm}} ''[[gretan#Middle English|greten, graten]]'' "to weep, cry, lament" (from {{ang}} ''[[grætan#Old English|grǣtan]]'' and {{non}} ''[[grata#Old Norse|grāta]]''). More at [[greet]], [[regret]].

===Verb===
{{en-verb|cr|i|ed}}

# {{intransitive}} To [[shed a tear|shed tears]]; to [[weep]].
#: ''That sad movie always makes me '''cry'''.''
# {{ambitransitive}} To [[shout]], [[scream]], [[yell]].
#: ''The captured bear cub tried to '''cry''' out to its mother.''

